of colour as well as white women directors, thus acknowledges both differences of the specific ethnic and social political contexts and shared concernsSince the turn of the millennium, a growing number of female filmmakers have appropriated the aesthetics of horror for their films. In this book, Patricia Pisters investigates contemporary women directors such as Ngozi Onwurah, Claire Denis, Lucile Hadžihalilović and Ana Lily Amirpour, who put ‘a poetics of horror’ to new use in their work, expanding the range of gendered and racialized perspectives in the horror genre.Exploring themes such as rage, trauma, sexuality, family ties and politics, New Blood in Contemporary Cinema takes on avenging women, bloody vampires, lustful witches, scary mothers, terrifying offspring and female Frankensteins. By following a red trail of blood, the book illuminates a new generation of women directors who have enlarged the general scope and stretched the emotional spectrum of the genre.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aFeminist film criticism. 0aHorror filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aHorror films. 0aWomen motion picture producers and directors. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / Direction & Production.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311078041340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147446697440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474466974423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474466974/original  a978-3-11-078041-3  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK